{
  "doc_id": "2679",
  "text": "Unfortunately, dietary starch per se apparently reduces secretion of pancreatic α-amylase, which is responsible for the initial hydrolysis of starch during its digestion [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . However, several reports have demonstrated that greater flow of protein to the small intestine of cattle can increase small intestinal starch digestion [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] , portal glucose appearance [CITATION_7] , and pancreatic α-amylase secretion [CITATION_8] . Many studies that have evaluated effects of small intestinal protein flows on small intestinal starch digestion and pancreatic α-amylase secretion used casein, and as a result, little is known about the effects of protein quality or AA flow on small intestinal starch digestion. Indeed, recent reports [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] suggest that interactions between supplemental proteins and pancreatic α-amylase might be affected by postruminal flows of α-glucosides and that requirements for nutritionally functional AA [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] to optimize pancreatic secretions may be proportional to starch appearing in the lumen of the small intestine in cattle.",
